TY  - JOUR
T1  - Contiguous Search: Exploration and Ambition on Uncharted Terrain
AU  - Urgun, Can
AU  - Yariv, Leeat
Y1  - 2024/08/26
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2025/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/732889
DO  - 10.1086/732889
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 522
EP  - 567
VL  - 133
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We provide a framework for analyzing search across correlated samples. The agent?a mineral prospecting team, a drug company, a politician?tracks observations over a Brownian path. The agent chooses the search speed and retrospectively picks the best observation when deciding to complete the search. We show that the optimal search speed is U-shaped: it is highest when approaching a breakthrough or when nearing search termination. Unlike search across independent samples, search optimally stops when observations are sufficiently discouraging, following a drawdown stopping boundary. We also show the tractability and features of optimal search contracts in our setting.
AB  - We provide a framework for analyzing search across correlated samples. The agent?a mineral prospecting team, a drug company, a politician?tracks observations over a Brownian path. The agent chooses the search speed and retrospectively picks the best observation when deciding to complete the search. We show that the optimal search speed is U-shaped: it is highest when approaching a breakthrough or when nearing search termination. Unlike search across independent samples, search optimally stops when observations are sufficiently discouraging, following a drawdown stopping boundary. We also show the tractability and features of optimal search contracts in our setting.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/732889
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/732889
Y2  - 2026/04/24
